---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Hi dotCMS — I'm Matías Baldanza"
  description="A personal application for the Developer Relations role at dotCMS."
  noindex
>
  <header class="hero">
    <img
      class="avatar"
      src="/images/avatar.jpg"
      alt="Matías Baldanza"
      width="112"
      height="112"
    />
    <h1>Hi dotCMS — I'm Matías.</h1>
    <p class="meta">
      An application for the Developer Relations role{" · "}
      <a href="/dotcms/resume">resumé</a>{" · "}
      <a href="mailto:matiasbaldanza@gmail.com">email me</a>
    </p>
  </header>

  <p>
    Rather than just tell you I can build developer experiences, I thought I'd
    start by building one: this mini-site is my application. It's a static
    Astro site with no client-side JavaScript, and the{" "}
    <a href="https://github.com/matiasbaldanza/matiasbaldanza.dev"
      >repo is public</a
    > — commit history, planning docs, and architecture decisions included.
    That's how I like to work: in the open, showing the process, not just the
    result.
  </p>

  <h2>About me</h2>
  <p>
    I'm a hands-on DevRel engineer. I research features, issues, and tools; I
    build working demos; I write the docs and tutorials that explain them; and
    I get in front of developers — on camera, in live workshops, in short- and
    long-form video, and in writing.
  </p>
  <p>
    Behind that is two decades of technical background — development, sysadmin,
    infrastructure, training — and more than ten years producing technical
    content in native-level English and Spanish. I've run daily live-coding
    streams to a hundred concurrent viewers, taught DevOps workshops with 300+
    sign-ups, and sustained a cadence of three short videos a week plus a
    long-form deep dive every month. And I test <em>everything</em> I ship in
    content: every environment, every command, every config.
  </p>
  <p>
    I care about one metric above all: how fast a developer gets from{" "}
    <em>"this looks interesting"</em> to{" "}
    <em>"I grok it and I'm using it effectively."</em>
  </p>

  <h2>About you</h2>
  <p>
    dotCMS sits in a spot I find genuinely interesting: a universal CMS that
    doesn't force the choice between traditional and headless. Developers meet
    you through REST and GraphQL APIs, SDKs, and integration guides — which
    means your developer experience <em>is</em> your product's first
    impression. A platform like that lives or dies by how quickly a developer
    gets a working "hello world" against a real content repository.
  </p>
  <p>
    That's exactly the kind of surface I've spent years working on: I've built
    and documented integrations across the CMS landscape — Contentful, Sanity,
    Strapi, Directus, Payload, Ghost, WordPress — and I know where developers
    stumble when they evaluate a content platform, because I've been the
    developer doing the evaluating, and the person writing the guide that gets
    them unstuck.
  </p>

  <h2>I'm that guy</h2>
  <p>
    You need someone who can own developer-facing content end to end. At DonWeb
    Cloud I created the developer content program from scratch — tutorials,
    guides, video, and demos across VPS, Linux, Docker, CI/CD, DNS/SSL, and CMS
    platforms — reporting directly to product and marketing leadership.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Demos and docs that actually run.</strong> I built and tested
      every environment, command, and config that shipped, and reviewed
      production images and scripts for correctness and reproducibility.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Comfortable in front of developers.</strong> Live programming
      workshops twice a month (300+ sign-ups, 150+ live), two years of daily
      unscripted live-coding on Twitch, and a steady video cadence in
      collaboration with an editor.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Bilingual by default.</strong> Native-level technical English and
      Spanish — content, workshops, and community, both directions.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Current on AI developer workflows.</strong> Claude Code, MCP
      servers, RAG pipelines, evals, agent-friendly documentation — the way
      developers will meet dotCMS next.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    I'd love to show you what that looks like applied to dotCMS. Have a look at
    my <a href="/dotcms/resume">resumé</a>, or just hit reply on the email that
    brought you here.
  </p>

  <p slot="footer">
    Matías Baldanza{" · "}
    <a href="mailto:matiasbaldanza@gmail.com">matiasbaldanza@gmail.com</a>{" · "}
    <a href="/dotcms/resume">resumé</a>{" · "}
    <a href="https://github.com/matiasbaldanza">GitHub</a>{" · "}
    <a href="https://linkedin.com/in/matiasbaldanza">LinkedIn</a>
  </p>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .hero {
    padding-top: var(--space-3);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .avatar {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .hero .meta {
    margin-top: 0.4rem;
  }
</style>
